<HEAD>Talk Show Hosts Say They're Ignored Despite Their Influence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Radio talk show hosts proved they're a force to be reckoned with during the congressional pay-raise brouhaha, deluging <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> with millions of tea bags from angry listeners. But they still feel ignored. So they're meeting in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> this weekend to do what other aggrieved minorities do: unite to demand more power. `` In the words of <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Dangerfield </PERSON>, ` We do n't get no respect,''' said organizer <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> radio station <ORGANIZATION> WRKO </ORGANIZATION>. `` The national media ... never took us very seriously. They think there's some conspiracy here.'' About 50 of the country's 225 radio talk show hosts began arriving Friday for the inaugural <ORGANIZATION> TalkRadio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, a two-day gab confab expected to include consumer activist <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, TV talk show host <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and political columnist <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a 65-year-old talk jockey who's been in the business since 1950, said he hoped the gathering would give visibility to a national movement that has given ordinary people a chance to be heard. `` There's a huge void where people feel they do n't have a voice anymore,'' he said. The voices at the conference are deep and smooth. The smiles are big. The words are vehement and well-rehearsed. `` There is no more representative government in this country anymore. It's all special interests,'' said <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> <PERSON> Crenshaw </PERSON> of WTKK-AM in <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` The reason politicians are afraid of talk radio is we have the ability to allow private citizens to talk to their government.'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> took the first step toward unifying the talk show hosts in February, when he was able to persuade his colleagues to lead a national protest against proposed federal pay increases. Coaxed by their local hosts, listeners sent their congressmen a ton of tea bags bearing the message: `` Read my tea bag: no 50 percent raise.'' The public pressure helped halt a raise for lawmakers, judges and other people on the federal payroll. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said he was encouraged by the cooperation of his on-air brethren to try to formalize their connections through a conference. The session got going Friday with an open mike to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area listeners. Today, the talk show hosts planned to talk to each other, exchanging ideas and formally organizing, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. Faneuil Hall, the venerable brick building where revolutionaries fomented independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and abolitionists railed against slavery, served as the stage for Friday's events. In the morning, <ORGANIZATION> WRKO </ORGANIZATION> host <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> leaned into one of the microphones and said, `` The people are sovereign, not the government,'' adding: `` Our elected representatives try ... to give Americans enough fat from the hog to keep people from rising up.'' His peers from across the country and about 125 listeners from around <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> took their seats. And in person, the talk show fans were as vociferous as their radio friends. `` I like to hear what the people say and not the politicians. We have a governor here who's a dictator,'' said <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Czapski </PERSON>, 67, of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Andover </LOCATION>, his face turning red. `` You've got me going,'' the retired tool and die plant manager said happily. <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Wofsey </PERSON>, 36, of <PERSON> Quincy </PERSON>, who works for a department store, said she's a frequent listener and talker. `` It's the satisfaction of voicing my opinion, to express it over the airwaves. With letter writing, there's no response,'' she said. `` You can get a response from the talk show.''
