<HEAD>Pennsylvania Labor Department Orders End to Gift Concern's Home Labor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MCCONNELLSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman struggling to keep her $ 1.7 million gift business alive says the state's enforcement of a law banning sewing work at home is unfair and has cost nearly 100 women their jobs. The state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> has ordered <ORGANIZATION> Overly-Raker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to stop using 100 or more homeworkers to piece together `` soft sculptures'' _ geese, cows, cats and other creations stuffed in cloth skins. <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Overly </PERSON>, the company's president, said she was unaware of the 1937 Industrial Homework Act and made no effort to hide the company's use of women sewing at home. The law prohibits anyone other than handicapped or those providing primary care for a handicapped family member from doing industrial work at home. Overly, a former teacher, founded the company in her basement 16 years ago with <PERSON> Freda </PERSON> <PERSON> Raker </PERSON>, a former secretary who handles the business' creative end. Since the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION> ordered the company to stop home production May 11 in response to a complaint, Overly said she began to hire the 30 or more seamstresses needed at a plant in a former dairy distribution building in southern <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>'s rural <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. `` The biggest hassle now is to find people who will come in,'' she said. Most of the women who had worked at home will lose their jobs because they have small children or can not get to the plant, she said. `` There's a lot of hardship going on because of this.'' One worker, <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Logsdon </PERSON>, said the $ 250 a month she earned supp