<DATELINE>FABIUS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It's no bull that state Sen. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Larraine </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON> owns a stud that was named after the state's governor. Actually, <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> is a bull _ all 800 pounds of him. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s odyssey began at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> two years ago, when 4H ` er <ORGANIZATION> Trista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parish </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, won the showmanship ribbon in the junior division for her cow, Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> presented her with the blue ribbon and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> was so moved she decided to name <PERSON> Phoebe </PERSON>'s first son after the state's favorite son Two months ago, <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON> was shopping for a breeding bull and bought <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, unaware of the stud's name. `` As soon as we heard, we said, ` Oh, no,''' said <PERSON> Hoffmann </PERSON>, a Democrat. She thought the name would be disrespectful of the governor, also a Democrat. In the end, she decided to steer away from calling the animal after the governor and changed the bovine's name to <PERSON> Bubba </PERSON>.
