<HEAD>U.S. to Interview Japanese Monk About American POWs in Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An American military attache will interview a <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> monk who has reportedly said he saw American prisoners in the re-education camp where he was held in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said today. The monk's daughter quoted her father as saying he shared a cell with three American prisoners for the last six years he spent in captivity. She said her father did not remember their names but described them as young and healthy. The monk, <PERSON> Iwanobu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>, 65, reportedly suffers from mental disorders and a speech impediment. He has been hospitalized since January when he returned to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> after being released from 14 years of imprisonment in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. In the past week he has given his first interviews to the Japanese media, raising interest with claims he saw Americans held since the Vietnam War. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> denies holding American prisoners, and recently it has cooperated with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials searching for remains of Americans missing in action. <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Keiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> today that her father communicated with the Americans in his cell through gestures. `` My father told me that when he asked them if they were Americans, they nodded,'' Ms. <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON> said during a telephone interview from her home in <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION> on Hokkaido, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s northernmost island. She said the prisoners were not allowed to speak to each other. Her report differed from one earlier in the week on the <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in which <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> was quoted as saying he saw `` five or six'' American POWs but never spoke with them and had been held apart from them. The location of the re-education camp has not been disclosed. Ms. <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> the <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> reporter must have misunderstood because her father told her several times he had been held with the Americans. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military attache will travel to <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION> on Sunday to interview <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said, speaking anonymously. He said Ms. <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON> met with a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> attache at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> recently to report on her father's remarks and that the information was forwarded to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for analysis. Ms. <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON> initially refused to speak with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, saying her father was too ill, according to the embassy spokesman. <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> suffers from mental disorders and a speech impediment, said <PERSON> Hidenori </PERSON> <PERSON> Hareyama </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Shiraishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokushukai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> on Hokkaido where <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> is being treated. Only <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>'s daughter can understand what he says and his speech is at times incoherent, <PERSON> Hareyama </PERSON> said. He refused to elaborate. <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monk, told the <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> that Vietnamese political prisoners also called the foreigners in the camp Americans. Ms. <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON> said her father does not remember the names of the three held in his cell but said they were still `` young and healthy.'' <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> told her he saw more American POWs, perhaps more than 10, before he suffered a stroke three years ago. `` My father is still afraid somebody will come and get him to throw him back in the Vietnamese prison,'' she said. <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>, formerly a city councilman in <LOCATION> Mibari </LOCATION> on Hokkaido, became a monk in 1966 and emigrated to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, where he set up a temple in <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION>, now called <LOCATION> Ho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. He was granted South Vietnamese citizenship in 1973, then was arrested in 1975 after the takeover of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> by communist forces. On Jan. 20, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> released <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> for humanitarian reasons after appeals by international human rights groups including <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. A total of 1,730 Americans are listed as missing in action in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, and 634 are missing in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> figures. The <LOCATION> Indochina </LOCATION> war ended in 1975 with communist victories over U.S.-supported governments in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>.
