<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian gunners shelled the coast north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> today, killing four people and wounding six, as an <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> envoy tried to halt 12 weeks of bloodshed between Syrian and Christian forces. A police spokesman said about 200 shells and rockets fired from Syrian batteries in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> exploded around the Christian ports of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> and Byblos early in the day. He said the fatalities were `` civilians killed near <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> when a 107mm <LOCATION> Katyusha </LOCATION> rocket hit a residential district near the harbor.'' The latest casualties brought the overall toll to 367 people killed and 1,427 wounded since the current round of violence broke out March 8 between <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> army units and an alliance of Syrian-Druse forces. The escalation coincided with the arrival in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> Lakhdar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ibrahimi </LOCATION>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> secretary general, in a renewed effort to stabilize a cease-fire. <LOCATION> Ibrahimi </LOCATION>, an Algerian, crossed <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s dividing Green Line for talks with <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> at the general's bunker office under the bomb-ravaged presidential palace of <LOCATION> Baabda </LOCATION>, east of the capital. Ibrahimi drove to Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> capital, Friday and held separate meetings with <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> in the nation's dual government, and <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON>. The Arab envoy was dispatched to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> by the