<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polish leader <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> says the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s resounding defeat in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s freest postwar elections may have been only a passing phenomenon. At the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today, a small group of Polish emigres protested Gen. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s visit, with one banner declaring: `` From <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to Peking, communism brings death.'' <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today after a one-day visit to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, and he met for 25 minutes with Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said the election results were `` a reflection not only of the attitudes but also of the emotions of the Polish people.'' `` But as you know, emotions are sometimes ephemeral,'' he said in an interview in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> with the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. He spoke in Polish, and his remarks were translated. Following a stop to lay a wreath at Polish war graves in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> today, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader was to meet with Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> for lunch at her country estate, <LOCATION> Chequers </LOCATION>. He plans to return to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> on Sunday. Members of Solidarity with Solidarity, a British-based group, organized their weekend vigil outside the embassy near a separate weeklong vigil outside the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are not saying that what happened in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> was as bad as the Chinese massacres,'' said protest organizer <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Rudewicz </PERSON>, referring to the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> army's attacks on pro-democracy protesters a week ago. `` But in 1981, it was Gen. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> who brought out the tanks onto the streets of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, when several hundred people were killed during martial law.'' Solidarity was crushed at that time and later banned. It was legalized under an April pact with the government. In a statement released Friday, Solidarity with Solidarity described <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> as `` a man decisively rejected by his nation'' in Sunday's elections. In the Polish voting for the new 100-seat <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, Solidarity won 92 seats and the other eight were undecided. Independent candidates were allowed to run for only 161 seats in the existing 460-seat Sejm, or lower house, but they won 160 of them. Only two of 35 top <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders and their allies running on a special list of unopposed candidates gained a majority of `` yes'' votes, allowing them to take seats without a new election. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said in a British newspaper interview this week that he would stand by the results and suggested that his <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> could lose power in totally free elections in 1993. In the <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> interview, <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> said the elections were not a `` football match ... it is a political process.'' He referred ruefully to his imposition of martial law in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1981 and his banning of the free trade union Solidarity. `` Sometimes it takes a long time before the revolution becomes civilized,'' said <PERSON> Jaru