<HEAD>Police Battle Students, Arrest 1,000</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 1,000 arrests, new clashes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of radical students today battled police with firebombs, rocks and clubs after protesters demanded the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government let them take part in a youth festival in communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Police reported more than 1,000 arrests. About 2,000 students fought riot police at two campuses in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> after they were blocked from marching into the streets to denounce President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>'s government and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Thirty student leaders were seized trying to reach the North Korean border for talks with communist officials, police said. About 1,500 students fought police with iron pipes, clubs and rocks at <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and about 500 students threw firebombs and rocks at police at nearby <ORGANIZATION> Sogang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Police hurled rocks back at students but did not use tear gas. `` Crush the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo regime!'' and `` Yankee go home!'' students yelled. Hundreds of students later battled police in central <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, hurling rocks and bricks. Riot squads used tear gas to break up the protesters and chased the students through the streets. Shoppers and pedestrians fled for cover. Troops and students were injured in the fighting, but the police had no figures on casualties. More than 1,000 students were arrested in the clashes or as they tried to reach the universities to take part in a second day of protests, police said. Police officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 20,000 riot police were deployed in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> to block the university demonstrations. About 6,000 troopers in green combat fatigues and visored helmets ringed <ORGANIZATION> Yonsei </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sogang </ORGANIZATION>, outnumbering the demonstrators. The protests came after students staged rallies at the two colleges to demand to take part in the 13th World Youth Festival next month in the North Korean capital of <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>. Radical students are calling for unification with the communist North. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has invited South Korean students to attend the youth festival, an athletic and cultural festival attended mainly by non-aligned and communist nations. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has accused the North of attempting to incite domestic unrest to weaken the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government. Student leaders charge that <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> keep the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula divided. They have called for the overthrow of <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> and expulsion of the 43,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops based in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The two Koreas are bitter rivals. They have clashed frequently over the years. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded the south in 1950 to start the Korean War. Radical students and dissidents have been calling for the fall of the <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> government, but they lack support because of their extreme views and violent tactics.
