<HEAD>Six Sentenced to Death by Stoning for Adultery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHAIRPUR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lower court today convicted six people of adultery and sentenced them to death by stoning under an Islamic law. Judge <PERSON> Mirza </PERSON> <PERSON> Saeed </PERSON> <PERSON> Beg </PERSON> invoked the controversial `` Hadood Ordinance'' enacted in 1979 by former President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON>. It was the first such ruling since Prime Minister <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> came to power in December. The U.S.-eductated Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> has pledged to press for repeal of the Islamic law, which imposes harsh punishment for moral offenses and limits women's rights. Beg's court convicted <PERSON> Ghulam </PERSON> <PERSON> Qadir </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Noor </PERSON> <PERSON> Khatoon </PERSON> of marrying illegally because Ms. <PERSON> Khatoon </PERSON> failed to secure a proper divorce from her previous husband, <PERSON> Shaikh </PERSON> <PERSON> Anver </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>. The court found four of <PERSON> Qadir </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>'s friends guilty as accomplices for helping arrange his marriage with Ms. <PERSON> Khatoon </PERSON>. No date was set for the executions. Members of the <PERSON> Khatoon </PERSON> and <PERSON> Qadir </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> families said they would appeal to a <LOCATION> Sindh </LOCATION> province high court. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has called for the repeal of all discriminatory Islamic laws promulgated under <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s 11-year rule. As chief of the army, Gen. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> toppled Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s father, Prime Minister <PERSON> Zulfikar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, in a 1977 military coup and had him executed two years later. <PERSO