<HEAD>Premier Proposes Sharp Reductions In Soviet Bureaucracy</HEAD>
<UNK>By ANDREW KATELL ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> today proposed sharp reductions in the vast Soviet bureaucracy and said the remaining government ministries should turn many of their powers over to the nation's 15 republics. Speaking to a joint session of the bicameral Supreme Soviet _ a new 542-member, full-time legislature _ <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said that of the 50 government ministries handling basic elements of the economy _ construction, transportation, agriculture and defense _ only 32 would remain. In addition, he told the lawmakers in a session broadcast live on radio and television that the number of members of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, or Cabinet that he heads, will be slashed from 100 to 10. The proposals, which the legislature is to vote on later this month, mark another step in President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s attempts to streamline the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> bureaucracy he has blamed for impeding his economic reforms They would also transfer many economic management functions to the 15 Soviet republics, many of which are campaigning for greater control over their affairs. <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON>, the 59-year-old technocrat re-elected premier on Wednesday, said the remaining ministries in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will focus on long-range planning and on scientific and technological help in the spheres they oversee. The ministries would leave the day-to-day managment they now provide to the republics. At the same time, two special commissions are to be formed, one to handle emergencies such as natural and man-made disasters and another to map economic reforms. Since <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> became <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader in March 1985, he has tried to rid Soviet society of a half-century of top-heavy, bureaucratic management `` by command'' epitomized by dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. The government ministries were a frequent target during 13 days of debate in the new Soviet parliament, the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> At one point, deputy <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Miloserdny </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION> blamed the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION> for short-sightedness that he said led to `` the disappearance from sale of the most basic consumer goods.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> himself urged the deputies to grill the ministers on why they are dragging their feet on reforms. He acknowledged complaints that government ministries `` are restructuring very slowly, if at all'' and said: `` We have to find out what is wrong.'' <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> announced nominees for the Cabinet posts today, and the Supreme Soviet is scheduled to hold confirmation hearings on them beginning June 19. The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> wrapped up its session Friday after hearing <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, 68, father of the Soviet human rights movement, say the parliament had `` not fulfilled its main task _ to establish a system of power to overcome economic and social problems, to put an end to ecological madness.'' The 1975 Nobel Peace Prize laureate also claimed that by electing <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> president in an uncontested election and investing him with far greater powers in his 5-year term, the parliament had given the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief `` absolute personal power.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, to loud applause in the Kremlin Palace of Congresses, vigorously objected to what he termed <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s attempt to `` abase'' the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' work.
