<HEAD>Train-Bus Collision Kills 31 in Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with number of passengers aboard the bus,
Tass' location of accident relative to Moscow, train's speed, background
on previous accident at that site. CORRECTS direction train heading. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A train traveling from a <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> resort rammed into a bus in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, killing 31 people and injuring at least 14 in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s second major train accident this week, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported today. The official Soviet news agency said the bus was crossing railroad tracks at the village of <LOCATION> Kamenskaya-Pogorelovo </LOCATION>, 640 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> when it was hit by the train Friday afternoon. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said a railroad worker had flagged the bus driver to move onto the tracks, but the report did not say if he faced punishment. The train, traveling at 50 mph from the popular <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> resort of <PERSON> Adler </PERSON> to the Russian city of <LOCATION> Voronezh </LOCATION>, could not stop in time to avoid colliding with the bus, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Twenty-nine people, including two children, were killed instantly and two died en route to a hospital. Fourteen people were hospitalized, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The news agency said 46 passengers were on the bus. It did not say whether the train carried passengers or freight. The accident happened at the same spot where 106 people were killed in a collision of two trains on Aug. 7, 1987, the news agency reported. On Sunday, a gas pipeline exploded as two passenger trains were passing on the Trans-Siberian Railroad 750 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>. At least 190 passengers were killed and hundreds injured. Last year, 464 Soviets were killed in accidents at railroad intersections, and 16,013 have died this year in all kinds of traffic accidents, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said.
