<HEAD>40 Hurt In Clash Between Socialists and Conservative Youth Groups</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALONICA, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of youths preparing for giant political rallies by <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s two major political parties clashed in <LOCATION> Salonica </LOCATION> on Saturday, and police said at least 40 people were injured. The clashes occurred before dawn as the youths belonging to the governing <ORGANIZATION> Panhellenic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> and the conservative <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> were putting up posters in this northern city in preparation for political rallies scheduled for Sunday and Monday night. Both parties are reportedly busing in thousands of supporters in a show of strength for the crucial June 18 national elections. Witnesses said the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> youths destroyed two house trailers and a campaign office used by the New Democrats. New Democracy youths reportedly retaliated by smashing the windows of a <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> campaign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> bureau </ORGANIZATION> and attacked the opposing youths with clubs. It took riot police two hours to restore calm. Police said at least 40 people were injured, most slightly, by clubs and stones.
