<HEAD>Moi Bans Homemade Beer In Kenya</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> arap </PERSON> <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> on Saturday banned the brewing and drinking of homemade beer in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, state radio reported. `` I am not prepared to lead a drunken nation,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kenya </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> as saying. `` From today, June 10, all brewing and drinking of traditional beer, even during traditional ceremonies, must cease.'' <PERSON> Moi </PERSON>, a church-goer and a teetotaler, made the announcement at a fund-raising event in <LOCATION> Kericho </LOCATION>, the headquarters of the tea-growing region in western <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, 160 miles from <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, various brands of traditional beer are made at home from fermented honey, sugar cane, coconut, and grains such as corn, millet and sorghum. Most people obtained a license from a low-ranking official before making such beer, but others simply did so without getting a permit. Homemade beer is a favorite drink among Kenyans, particularly in the countryside, during social occasions such as weddings and funerals. <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> did not mention other alcoholic beverages. <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> manufactures whiskey, vodka, gin, liquor, four commercial beers and small quantities of fruit wines.
