<FIRST>u w AM-China-WhoKnows?     06-10 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Who Knows?,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush and His Old China Hands Have Few Tea Leaves to Read</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Intelligence experts say they're not surprised that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> admits he ca n't say for sure `` who's calling the shots'' in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` Real time intelligence _ that is what is happening now _ is almost impossible to come by,'' said one administration official. The official, who is familiar with the daily intelligence briefings prepared by the Departments of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> and other sources, said the president's comment that the situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is `` very, very murky'' came directly from such reports. At one point, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> even joked about the problem, saying he'd called <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 84-ear-old leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, but `` the line was busy I could n't get through.'' The reason <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have so little information about who may or may not be in power at any given time, or who gave specific orders for the savage attack on the pro-democracy demonstrators, is quite simple, the experts say. `` There's no access. ... If they do n't want to respond to the president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, they sure as hell are n't going to respond to the ambassador,'' the administration official said. He, and others speaking on intelligence matters, spoke only on condition that their names and exact titles not be used. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which only began to open up during the past decade, has traditionally posed a problem for foreigners seeking detailed information. The leaders sequester themselves in special compounds and are not seen unless they wish to be seen. They tend to keep their decisions within a very tight circle, and for the most part, have had nearly complete control over the mass media. The dearth of human intelligence _ that gleaned by personal contact _ has been `` a big difficulty'' in the current unrest, the administration official said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomats tend to be exposed to their counterparts who `` spout the party line'' in normal times, said another source familiar with the diplomatic scene in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. `` So when there is a undoubted conflict within the party, government and top military leadership, they are especially careful to keep it obscure from the rest of the world,'' said the diplomatic source. During the past week, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lilley </PERSON> has met twice with the vice foreign minister in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> has called the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> twice. Embassy officials have contacted officials from the Chinese ministry of national defense, the ministry of education and the civil aviation administration. Also, contacts have taken place with some <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> military officers who are personally acquainted with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, and they have been providing some information. `` But it's not very satisfactory,'' the administration official said The official admitted with some frustration that `` we do n't have any feel for what is going on'' in what he called `` the dark stretches'' of provincial <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The diplomatic source said the government has `` ample reports'' about the situation in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. `` But there is an important distinction between being able to observe what is going on the outside and having access to the inner workings of the party and government,'' he said. The administration official pointed out that information culled from technical sources such as satellite photos or electronic surveillance can only go so far in providing up-to-date information. `` Overhead photos ... pictures of troops massed and locations and tanks, that is n't going to tell you who does what to whom'' during a group-by-group or person-to-person struggle for political power, said the official. Although he refused to specifically discuss electronic surveillance, the official noted that the sheer volume of information poses a problem. `` You have a whole mass of information to sort out ... it has to translated, analyzed, and sometimes only after the fact ... do you find something has happened,'' he said. One important source of information is the news media, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials freely admitted they had their eyes glued to the round-the-clock coverage provided by the 24-hour <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>. `` <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> has been one of the sturdy resources for information'' during the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> crackdown, the administration official said. `` We can not presume to do without the information that the media transmit,'' said another, calling the presence of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television networks `` of tremendous importance.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also cooperates with other foreign embassies in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but `` everybody's been somewhat embarrassed, really, at how difficult and unsuccessful they've been in getting any information,'' the administration official said. `` We're all in the same boat.'' Sometimes, the official said, expectations are just too high. `` It's a magic word _ people really think that ` intelligence' people are omniscient, but boy, they sure are n't,'' the official said
</TEXT>
