<HEAD>Harvard Student Convicted of Six Armed, Ski-Mask Robberies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A onetime altar boy who escaped the barrio to become a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> student was convicted of pulling six armed robberies during college vacations. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Razo </PERSON>, 22, showed no emotion as he was convicted Friday by an <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury. `` I think that none of us wanted to find him guilty,'' said juror <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Montanye </PERSON>. `` But there was just too much evidence on most of the counts. And we could n't get his excellent memory out of our minds.'' The prosecution rested heavily on a videotaped confession in which <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> recounted with vivid detail the holdups by a gunman in a ski mask. Defense attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> maintained it was a false confession given in a stupor induced by the drug phencyclidine, better known as PCP or angel dust. Jurors, who deliberated three days, acquitted <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> of four other robbery counts, including two that he had confessed to. But they also convicted him of trying to escape from police after his arrest in 1987. He faces a maximum sentence of 15 years and four months in prison. Sentencing is scheduled for Aug. 4. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> was charged with committing 10 armed robberies between December 1985 and June 1987. In the confession, <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> told detectives he robbed fast-food restaurants, grocery stores, a dairy and a drug store. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON> testified that he confessed to the robberies in a drug-driven schizophrenic episode, describing crimes actually committed by a friend and drug dealer, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Longoria </PERSON>. When Deputy District Attorney <PERSON> Ravi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mehta </PERSON> pointed out that the friend was in jail during three of the robberies, <PERSON> Razo </PERSON>'s lawyer suggested those holdups were committed by his client's younger brother, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON>. <PERSON> Razo </PERSON>, a product of a poor <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Habra </ORGANIZATION> neighborhood was an altar boy and <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> `` Boy of the Year,'' and an `` A'' student at his <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> high school. A standout prep football player, he was wooed by more than 60 colleges when he graduated. He chose a scholarship to <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, where just 4.7 percent of the student body is Hispanic. As a freshman in 1985, he decided to major in psychology. `` He always said, ` Look how good I'm doing. I'm Mexican. I'm trying to make it in a white world,''' his sister, <PERSON> Martha </PERSON>, once told an interviewer But in a jail interview right after his confession and arrest in July 1987, he said: `` At <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, I did n't fit. I'm a homeboy now.''
