<HEAD>Small Fire Found in Navy Vessel; 14 Sailors Suffer Smoke Inhalation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH NAVAL STATION, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fourteen sailors suffered smoke inhalation when a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> helicopter carrier caught fire in port, but there was no serious damage to the ship. The Peleliu, an amphibious assault ship used as a helicopter carrier, caught fire on Friday night, Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> said. The fire apparently broke out in the circuit breaker room, where a cable from the shore powers the ship while in port. The cause of the fire was not known, but an investigation was under way. The damage was minimal and the 14 sailors who suffered smoke inhalation were treated and returned to onboard duty by Saturday morning, <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> said. The fire was put out by approximately 10:30 p.m., less then 20 minutes after it was discovered, and repairs to the ship will be made by the crew. The Peleliu had recently returned from operations, but <PERSON> Chesser </PERSON> did not know the nature of the assignment. The ship normally has a crew of 900. <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> is located 20 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>.
