<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, which closed its public schools during a student-led uprising last year, will begin reopening them soon. The spokesman for <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s ruling military council, Col. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Thein </PERSON>, told reporters Friday that primary schools will open June 19 `` followed by the reopening of middle schools and high schools.'' He did not say if universities would be allowed to reopen. They were the focal point of the uprising from March to September in 1988. Thousands of protesters were killed in a series of harsh crackdowns on dissent before the army finally re-established control on Sept. 18. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> said attendance at the nation's public schools will not be compulsory. He also warned that student activism will not be tolerated.
