<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and his family took a whitewater rafting trip down <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s oldest river Saturday after the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> lowered the water level for a smoother ride. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, his wife, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON>, and children <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Corinne </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> put their raft into the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> about 10:30 a.m., accompanied by guides and three rafts filled with <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents. The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> informed raft operators that it would decrease flow from <LOCATION> Bluestone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dam </LOCATION>, 40 miles upriver, from 14,000 cubic feet per second Friday to 8,000-10 ,000 cfs Saturday, said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanger </PERSON>, who runs <ORGANIZATION> Songer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whitewater </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fayetteville </LOCATION> `` He'll have a ` kinder, gentler' ride,'' said <PERSON> Hanger </PERSON>, adding that recent rains also would smooth the course over rapids from <ORGANIZATION> Cunard </ORGANIZATION> to Fayette Station. The Quayles took a shorter trip than most rafters _ three hours instead of four _ and exited the river about a mile downriver from the usual landing. The vice president spoke with reporters before the trip but not afterward. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> remarked on <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s beauty, and mentioned a <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration environmental proposal that could reduce demand for the state's