ad started its trip upriver at <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON> was forced to tie up for 1 -LCB- hours along the river bank and wait until after the Quayles took off. `` Good morning, Mr. Vice President,'' some of the rafters shouted when the <ORGANIZATION> Quayles </ORGANIZATION> passed them. Other rafters were displeased that the river was n't at full strength. `` I was expecting something a little more challenging,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, Del. `` But I understand. After all, he is the vice president.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> made a 45-mile stretch of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> part of the national park system in 1978, shortly after the area was opened up by the completion of four-lane <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> 19 over the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gorge </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Fayette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION>.
