<HEAD>Japan's 1988 Foreign Aid Totals $9.1 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s aid to Third World nations rose 22.5 percent to $ 9.1 billion last year, second only to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' estimated $ 9.8 billion in grants to developing countries, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Saturday Development aid as a percentage of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s gross national product was 0.32 percent, up from the previous year's 0.31 percent, the ministry said in an annual report. Of the total, $ 6.4 billion went directly to developing nations, the report said. That included $ 2.9 billion in grants and $ 3.5 billion in loans. Indirect assistance through the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and other international organizations was $ 2.7 billion, up 22.9 percent over 1987, the report said. The government earmarked $ 5.4 billion in the 1989 budget in direct funding, ministry officials said. An additional $ 5 billion in development assistance will be provided in loans and investments, bringing total aid to more than $ 10 billion. That would make <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> the world's largest aid donor, officials said. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has felt foreign pressure in recent years to do more for developing nations.
