<HEAD>Lt. Gov. Wilder Nominated For Virginia Governorship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, in his quest to become the first black governor since Reconstruction, was tapped Saturday as the Democratic nominee at the party convention. `` You had the courage to stand with me four years ago,'' <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> said, in reference to his 1985 underdog campaign that made him the first black elected to statewide office in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. Also nominated were businessman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beyer </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> for lieutenant governor and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> for a second term as attorney general. Under state law, Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON> can not run for a second consecutive term. `` The experts said it could n't be done,'' said <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, a 58-year-old father of three whose daughter <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>, an artist, gave one of the seconding speeches for his nomination. `` But together, we did it.'' Ms. <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> said her father taught her to be undaunted by risks. A Wilder victory on Nov. 7 would make him the first elected black governor in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history. At least one black served as governor, but not as an elected governor, for a time in the South during the period after the Civil War. His Republican opponent will be chosen Tuesday in a bitterly contested primary from among former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trible </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, former Attorney General <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Stanford </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parris </PERSON>. Polls released last week showed the three <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> contenders neck-and-neck and each slightly leading <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> in a head-to-head contest. But the Democratic ticket has swept all three offices in the last two statewide elections, including <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s precedent-setting victory as lieutenant governor four years ago `` The people of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> do not want to turn back,'' <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> said. `` They know <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> is moving in the right direction. They want to continue our progress and prosperity.'' <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON> and his predecessor, former Gov. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>, even though he has publicly feuded with both men on issues ranging from tax policy to giving credit for election victories. At the convention, the three men clasped hands and raised them as the 5,300 delegates and alternates cheered. <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>, now a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator, said in a seconding speech for <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> that their differences `` pale by comparison to what those Republicans are saying about each other.'' He said he might not have been elected lieutenant governor in 1977 and governor in 1981 without <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s help. <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON>, who was the target of a coal miners' protest at the convention, said <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> reminds him of the verse of poetry that ends, `` Paddle your own canoe.'' `` Well, I've looked out the window of the governor's office on more than one occasion and, sure enough, there was <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> paddling by. But he was always nice about it. He always waved,'' <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON> said. He said he admires <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> because `` he knows what he believes in and has the courage to stand and be counted.'' About 150 labor delegates at the convention stood silently and turned their backs to <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON> while the governor delivered the keynote speech. The protest was over the sending of state troopers to the <LOCATION> southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> mountains </LOCATION>, where some 1,700 members of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union have been on strike since April against the <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> operations. `` We think he's turned his back on us by putting at least a third of the state police out there escorting coal trucks and harassing our people,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Church </PERSON>, a convention delegate from <LOCATION> Wise </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and former president of the <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, a grandson of slaves and a former state senator from <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, came to the convention unopposed for the nomination. A bid by state Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <PERSON> Wythe </PERSON> drew little support and <PERSON> Bird </PERSON> dropped out of the contest earlier this year.
