<HEAD>Slain Chinese Students Honored by White House, Bishop</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The two ceremonies ...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with demonstrations in Washington, New Jersey, edit for transition; picks
up 4th graf, `The two ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The bishop of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, jailed for 30 years by the Chinese Communists until his May 1988 release, called for freedom and peace in his homeland during a memorial Mass on Saturday for the students slain in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Ignatius </PERSON> <PERSON> Kung </PERSON>, who was released from a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> prison for medical reasons, made his comments shortly after the secretary of the interior laid a memorial wreath at the Statue of Liberty `` as an eternal reminder of the cause'' for which the students died. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, 500 to 600 people protested outside the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, and erected a 20-foot plaster replica of the Statue of Liberty in a nearby park. The statue, however, was barely visible from the embassy because it was largely shielded by tall bushes. About 200 Chinese students and supporters demonstrated in the northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Morristown </LOCATION> under banners with such messages as `` Give Me Freedom Or Give Me Death'' and `` Students In <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, We Stand On Your Side.'' The two ceremonies in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> marked the second consecutive day of pro-student activities in the city in the wake of last weekend's shootings in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> On Friday, more than 15,000 people packed Dag Hammarskjold Plaza outide the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> after a memorial service and mock funeral procession through <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION>. Interior Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, saying the spirit of the pro-democracy forces would never be forgotten, placed the memorial wreath on <LOCATION> Liberty </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> at a brief Saturday morning ceremony. `` Sadly, we come here today to commemorate those who lost their lives in the quest for freedom in their own lands,'' said <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>. `` We were horrified by the brutal reminder that there are strong forces in this world who seek to snuff out the flame of liberty.'' <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>, standing beneath the Statue of Liberty, thanked the students for inspiring Americans by erecting the <ORGANIZATION> Goddess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, a statue inspired by Miss Liberty that stood in Tiananmen Square. Later, about 100 people filled the <ORGANIZATION> Transfiguration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION> to hear <PERSON> Kung </PERSON> deliver his comments. `` I am happy to be here, but at the same time very sad,'' <PERSON> Kung </PERSON> said in his sermon, which was read by a translator. `` I am happy to pray for human rights, but sad for the innocent youths who have been brutally murdered.'' The 88-year-old bishop was jailed in 1958 for his refusal to renounce papal authority. Since his release last year, <PERSON> Kung </PERSON> has since been receiving medical treatment in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION> `` The death of the Chinese young students is a great tragedy in Chinese history. All of you who live in freedom, through your prayers, must support our suffering brethren,'' said <PERSON> Kung </PERSON>. After saying Mass, the frail, bespectacled bishop blessed a shrine inside the church set up to `` <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square martyrs.'' A dozen wreaths sent by various groups in <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION> surrounded the shrine. After the Mass, dozens of parishioners lined up to pray at the memorial. In the schoolyard adjoining the church, pro-student groups set up tables to collect donations in the fight for democracy. There was one pocket of support for the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government's decision to use military force against the students <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Flounders </PERSON>, a member of the national committee of the <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said the socialist organization backed the Chinese government. `` We feel it's in the interest of the working people and oppressed people all over the world to support the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government,'' she said, labeling the student uprising `` a counter-revolutionary development.''
