<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocky Flats Presents One Image Externally; Has Another Internally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two faces of the Rocky Flats nuclear plant were presented by its operators and its federal overseers, an affidavit and internal memos revealed after federal raids shut down the facility as unsafe last week. Hazardous wastes were burned illegally in a plutonium reprocessing building while it was closed for safety violations, the affidavit states, yet the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> paid <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION>' managers bonuses each year as rewards for production and management A July 1986 Energy Department internal memorandum said <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> was `` in poor condition generally in terms of environmental compliance'' and its permit applications were `` grossly deficient.'' The memo also indicated some of the plant's waste facilities were `` patently illegal.'' Plutonium triggers are made at the plant, northwest of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. Yet an ad for <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the facility's operator, appears in the current edition of a metropolitan weekly, the <ORGANIZATION> Broomfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION>, inviting the public to tour the plant. Officials said the tours were the company's method of explaining to neighboring communities how the nuclear weapons plant operated and why. The Rocky Mountain News quoted an unidentified <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> spokesman as saying that the ad was placed before the investigation. Another DOE memo, written July 14, 1986, said favorable news media attention had been garnered for Rocky Flats officials who negotiated a cleanup agreement with regulators, rather than the bad press they might have deserved. `` Much of the good press we have gotten from the agreement ... has taken attention away from just how really bad this site is,'' the memo said. Energy Department officials supported the statements of <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> executives about plant safety and performance they allegedly knew were false, according to the affidavit that was unsealed Friday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here. The affidavit was made public after it had been used earlier in the week by federal agents to obtain warrants for the raids. Some of Rocky Flats' top managers since 1980 are among the DOE and <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> officials named in the affidavit as possible co-conspirators in violation of hazardous waste laws. They include <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Whiteman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Romatowski </PERSON>, as well as <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> executives <PERSON> Dominic </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchini </PERSON> and J.E. Door. But representatives of the department and <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment on the affidavit. It says DOE and <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> officials are suspected of collaborating on making low waste estimates at Rocky Flats. They also are accused of making false statements regarding waste disposal at the facility. At that time, the plant's plutonium-reprocessing facility, Building 771, was supposed to be shut down for four months afer three safety inspectors were accidentally exposed to radiation. But the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, using infrared cameras during flights over Rocky Flats in December, detected burning in an incinerator in Building 771. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Whiteman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sanchini </PERSON> publicly were saying the building totally was shut down. <PERSON> Whiteman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dorr </PERSON> also were accused of misleading regulators in 1985 by certifying that Rocky Flats' groundwater monitoring system complied with federal requirements. The affidavit says that certification was found to be false and in violation of federal law. <PERSON> Whiteman </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials were accused of claiming that a number of wastes were nonhazardous, when in fact they were hazardous. A Nov. 13, 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> memo by <PERSON> Romatowski </PERSON> to other department officials advised that the agency should resist the efforts of environmental and public health authorities trying to clean up Rocky Flats. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> also is conducting an investigation into performance bonuses awarded Rocky Flats' managers. The DOE paid bonuses each year, ranging from $ 2.3 million in 1981 to $ 9.4 million last year, to reward <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> for its production and management performance at Rocky Flats. In addition to the raid by <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> agents, the plant also came under fire Wednesday from the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, which announced it had found 25 environmental and procedural violations at the plant.
