<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Duel Kills 4, Amid Arab Mediation Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian and Christian gunners exchanged rocket and artillery fire Saturday, killing four people and wounding 12. Arab officials, meanwhile, sought to halt the fighting and reportedly were trying to gain support for a peace plan to end <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year civil war. A police spokesman said the Syrians, entrenched in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, blasted the Christian coastline north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> with 130mm howitzer shells and 107mm rockets. One round struck a residential district near the port of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION>, 12 miles north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, killing four people and wounding seven, he said on condition of anonymity. Five other civilians were wounded in a retaliatory barrage on west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> during which <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> units under Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> opened up with 155mm howitzers, he said. The latest casualties brought the overall toll to 367 people killed and 1,432 wounded since the latest round of fighting began on March 8 between <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s 20,000 forces and allied Syrian and Druse Moslem fighters. The clash began when <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s forces blockaded illegal ports run by Moslem militias that <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> said cost the state treasury about $ 100 million yearly. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> responded by blockading the 310-square-mile Christian enclave. Thuds of exploding shells shook the capital as <PERSON> Lakhdar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibrahimi </PERSON>, an Arab League envoy, shuttled twice between the Christian and Moslem sectors for talks with <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s dual government, and <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>, his Moslem rival. The <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> called a cease-fire on May 11 but the fighting did not stop. The league renewed the call at a summit meeting in <LOCATION> Casablanca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, May 23-26 and appointed a three-member committee to devise a peace plan. But Syrian forces kept shelling the Christian coastline, claiming they wanted to prevent Iraqi supplies from reaching <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> by sea. These barrages have drawn occasional retaliation from <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s forces. <LOCATION> Ibrahimi </LOCATION>, an Algerian diplomat, left for <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> later Saturday. The Arab committee is comprised of <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>'s King <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, King Fahd of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and President <PERSON> Chadli </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendjedid </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION>. Their foreign ministers arrived in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, Saturday after three days of talks in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> with Syrian President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Farouk </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Sharaa </PERSON>, who reportedly pledged to assist their mission. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, the Arab world's traditional rivals, are on opposite sides of the Lebanese civil war. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, with 40,000 troops in northern and eastern provinces as well as west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, is the Moslems' main supporter. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> supports <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, who has vowed to drive the Syrians out of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The independent <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> An-Nahar </ORGANIZATION> said the Arab foreign ministers were soliciting support for a seven-point settlement proposal. The plan, according to the paper, calls for `` exerting international pressure on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to withdraw its forces from south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has occupied a self-designated `` security sone'' in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> since 1985 in an effort to stop cross-border guerrilla raids. According to An-Nahar, the peace proposal would include the `` deployment of an Algerian force'' along a 75-mile-long coastal stretch from <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>, 25 miles south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, to prevent the import and export of illegal goods. It also calls for lifting all sea, land and air blockades.
