<SECOND>AM-China-Shanghai,0937</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arrests, Government Warnings Keep China's Largest City Under Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHANGHAI, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Millions of bicycles clog cratered streets, electric trolleys lumber down tree-shaded avenues and dim neon signs flicker above hole-in-the-wall bars. <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> grinds on after authorities made some arrests and issued warnings of tougher action aimed at preventing <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s largest city from becoming the new focal point for the pro-democracy movement crushed in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> last week. The fist of authority has come down, less forcefully in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> than elsewhere, but strong enough to stifle the reappearing protests. Security forces have swept through <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> cities in recent days arresting scores of students and workers, including at least 21 in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>. In the last few days protesters wrought havoc on <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>'s traffic, blocking intersections with buses and concrete barricades On Friday they held a rally in People's Square that drew 50,000 supporters _ largest anywhere in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> since the bloody suppression of the democracy uprising June 3-4 that left at least 3,000 dead Facing virtually no opposition from authorities in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, which unlike <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> is not under martial law, activists seemed headed toward shifting the focus of the fight for freedom and expanded rights to this city of 12 million. <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Zhu </PERSON> <PERSON> Rongji </PERSON> gave what was viewed as a conciliatory speech Thursday, urging civic obedience so troops would not be called into the city. But authorities issued a clear warning against further unrest. `` We want to sternly warn certain ... students not to go any further on this dangerous road,'' <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> radio said Saturday. `` There is a limit to the restraint of the people of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>.'' There was also a heavy police presence Saturday, with a motorcade of 17 police motorcycles with sidecars and a small convoy of trucks carrying workers urging rigid support of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> swooping through the city. A major handicap for students' propaganda efforts is the lack of news about what has happened in the capital 670 miles to the northwest. `` The government says 23 students were killed, but how do we know way down here in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>?'' asked a 33-year-old delivery man. `` We know the students say many more were killed than the government says, but we have no idea who's right,'' a mechanic said. `` We do n't get any news.'' Since before last week's bloody crackdown in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, provincial students had been returning to the countryside to inform the masses about the revolution. But <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> students have not been particularly energetic in spreading the word. There were scattered posters in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> earlier this week calling for a general strike, but they have largely disappeared, residents say. Instead, <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> citizens seem to be absorbed in other kinds of posters. In the city center, people stared intently at pictures of a bodybuilding contest, movie promotions and shoe advertisements tacked up along raucous <LOCATION> Nanjing </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION>. Several clusters of people gathered at People's Square Saturday to exchange opinions about the previous day's mass rally. `` I'm outraged, but I'm very afraid. I do n't dare speak out,'' a research scientist said. `` Our media is just communist party propaganda. We all listen to the <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> BBC </ORGANIZATION> broadcasts every day to hear the truth.'' Several people around him nodded. Like all those interviewed in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, the scientist insisted that his name not be used. The Chinese government began a new form of terror Saturday, playing foreign news reports on television and urging informers to identify Chinese who spoke on camera. About 200 students from <PERSON> Shahghai </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fudan </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tongji </ORGANIZATION> universities held a rally and sit-in in front of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> police headquarters to demand the release of nine labor leaders arrested Friday. `` If they decided to press charges then they must do so in the open, but they insist on doing it secretly,'' said a student leader from <ORGANIZATION> Tongji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> at the protest. The arrests appeared to be part of a nationwide campaign to create a split between students and workers. By cracking down on labor, authorities undermine a main source of support for the student movement. At <ORGANIZATION> Fudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, about 90 percent of the students have returned to their homes out of fear of troops entering campus to arrest students. Along the main path into campus there is an 8-foot plastic foam model of the statue of liberty made by a neighboring school and paraded around the city in marches before the May 20 imposition of martial law in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Student leaders were divided earlier this week over whether to continue disrupting city life. `` We finally agreed to an end to the barricades because the loss in production caused by them becomes the people's burden,'' one senior said. Diplomatic sources estimated production fell off in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, a major industrial base, by as much as 50 percent after the barricades caused widespread absenteeism at factories. With arrests stepping up in the last few days, it is time for the democracy movement to pause and assess its lessons, students interviewed at <LOCATION> Fudan </LOCATION> said. `` Most peasants do n't understand our 1989 movement at all,'' one freshman said. `` We must now concentrate on bringing the peasants into play. Sheer fear and a need for quiet reflection are thus likely to keep <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> from becoming the kind of rallying point for democracy that <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was. `` The people of <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> are not cowards,'' said a young bank teller at People's Square. `` But we are afraid of getting killed.''
