<HEAD>Palestinian Child Killed, 29 Arabs Wounded in Clashes with Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli soldiers opened fire Saturday on Palestinians protesting new identity cards and an 8-year-old boy was struck in the chest and fatally wounded, a doctor reported. Hospital officials said the boy was one of 30 Arabs wounded during clashes with troops in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. According to residents of the Jabaliya refugee camp in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, soldiers in jeeps used loudspeakers to announce that a week-long military curfew on the strip would be lifted to allow residents to obtain new computerized identity cards. The cards are needed for Palestinians to work in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Khader </PERSON> <PERSON> Muranakh </PERSON>, a camp resident, said about 200 Palestinians began a protest march shouting slogans against the new cards. `` Youths started pelting the troops with stones and the soldiers then opened fired,'' said <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> nurse <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamudeh </PERSON>. A doctor at the U.N. Relief and <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> clinic in the camp said <PERSON> Shadi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziad </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabah </PERSON> <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>, 8, was hit in the chest by a rubbet-coated metal pellet and died despite an emergency operation. <PERSON> Muranakh </PERSON> said the boy was standing outside his uncle's home watching the demonstration when troops opened fire from about two yards away and wounded him. An army spokesman confirmed the death, but gave the boy's age as 12. The spokesman did not provide the circumstances of the death. Army officials have accused <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> activists of encouraging children to participate in protests to act as shields for older organizers and to serve propaganda purposes when they are wounded. <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>'s death raised to 514 the number of Palestinians killed since the uprising began 18 months ago. Twenty-two Israelis also have been slain in the violence. <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reports said 28 Palestinians, including <PERSON> Awad </PERSON>, were wounded in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. They said two Palestinians were wounded in clashes in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION>. The army announced late Saturday that the curfew would remain in effect on the <LOCATION> Jabaliya </LOCATION> refugee camp when it is lifted from the rest of the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> on Sunday. Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said in a radio interview that the army had succeeded in breaking a boycott ordered by the underground leadership of the uprising. The leadership called on the 1.7 million Palestinians in the occupied lands to stop paying taxes, tear up identity cards, and not cooperate with the military government. `` The opposite has happened,'' <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> said. `` The individual today needs and depends on the civil administration, and therefore there is no more talk of a popular revolt.'' `` On the other hand, we have not been able to prevail over the sporadic stone throwings,'' he said.
