<HEAD>U.S. To Interview Monk Who Reportedly Saw American POWs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is sending a military attache to interview a <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> monk who reportedly saw American POWs in Vietnamese prison camps recently, despite <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>'s assertions that it holds no prisoners. The <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monk, <PERSON> Iwanobu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>, 65, has been hospitalized in northern <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> with what are termed mental and physical problems since he was freed in January after 14 years' imprisonment in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. In the past week, Japanese media reports and his daughter have said that <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> shared a cell with Americans in the re-education camp where he was held. The Vietnamese Embassy in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> denied the claims, reiterating that <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> holds no prisoners from the war, which ended in 1975. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has for years pressed <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> for an accounting of the 1,730 Americans listed as missing in action in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and 634 missing elsewhere in the war zone. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Saturday that a military attache planned to fly to northern <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION> Sunday to interview <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> and the information will be relayed to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for analysis. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sought to interview <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> earlier but until now had been turned down by his daughter, <PERSON> Keiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON>, on grounds he was too ill, said the embassy spokesman on condition of anonymity. Ms. <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON> on Saturday said her father had shared a cell with three American prisoners for the last six years before returning to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` My father told me that when he asked them if they were Americans, they nodded,'' Ms. <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON> said in an interview from her home in <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION> on Hokkaido, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s northernmost island. The prisoners were not allowed to speak to each other, she said. A spokesman for the hospital where <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> is being treated said he suffers from mental disorders and a speech impediment, and only his daughter can understand what he says. <PERSON> Hidenori </PERSON> <PERSON> Hareyama </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Shiraishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokushukai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> on Hokkaido said that <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON>'s speech is at times incoherent. Ms. <PERSON> Takutsaka </PERSON> said her father had a stroke three years ago. <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> had been a city councilman in <LOCATION> Mibari </LOCATION> on Hokkaido before he became a monk in 1966 and emigrated to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. He set up a temple in <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION>, now <LOCATION> Ho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Minh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, and became a South Vietnamese citizen in 1973. He was arrested in 1975, after the takeover of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> by Communist forces. On Jan. 20, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> released him on humanitarian grounds after appeals from international human rights groups including <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Takatsuka </PERSON> said her father does not remember the names of the three held in his cell, but said they were still `` young and healthy.'' <PERSON> Yoshida </PERSON> told her he saw more American POWs, perhaps more than 10, before he suffered a stroke. `` My father is still afraid somebody will come and get him to throw him back in the Vietnamese prison,'' she said.
