<HEAD>Reports 31 Killed in Bus-Train Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A train crashed into a bus in a village southwest of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and 31 people were killed in the second major railway accident in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in less than a week, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported Saturday. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the accident occurred Friday afternoon after a railroad worker flagged the bus driver to go ahead and cross the tracks. The vehicle was struck by the train traveling 50 mph. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said at least 14 people were injured in the accident in <LOCATION> Kamenskaya-Pogorelovo </LOCATION>, 640 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The train had left the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> resort of <PERSON> Adler </PERSON> and was en route to <LOCATION> Voronezh </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. It reported the bus was carrying 46 passengers but it did not say if the train was a freight or passenger train and if all of the casualties were from the bus or if some were aboard the train. The agency said the accident happened at the same crossing where 106 people were killed in a collision of two trains on Aug. 7, 1987. Last Sunday gas from a pipeline exploded as two passenger trains were passing on the Trans-Siberian Railroad 750 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>. At least 190 passengers were killed and hundreds injured. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said 464 people were killed in accidents at Soviet railroad crossings last year.
