<DATELINE>HYERES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Spaggiari </PERSON>, mastermind of the spectacular `` sewer gang'' bank heist and on the run for 12 years, died and his body was left outside his mother's house by friends on Saturday, police and the thief's lawyer reported. Police said <PERSON> Spaggiari </PERSON>'s body was brought to his mother's home in this <LOCATION> Riviera </LOCATION> city early Saturday by two men who fled. Police specialists confirmed the body was that of <LOCATION> Spaggiari </LOCATION>, 57, who underwent plastic surgery after <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s most famous bank job in 1976. <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Peyrat </PERSON>, <PERSON> Spaggiari </PERSON>'s lawyer, said his client died of lung cancer on Friday. <PERSON> Spaggiari </PERSON>, who had a photography business in Nice, formed the gang of `` sewer rats'' who tunneled their way into the <ORGANIZATION> Societe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Generale </ORGANIZATION> bank in <ORGANIZATION> Nice </ORGANIZATION> and over a weekend, July 17-19, 1976, opened 337 safe deposit boxes. They made off with gold, jewelry and negotiable paper worth an estimated $ 6,835,812. The gang paddled a mile down a sewer and dug a tunnel 25 feet long from the sewer to the back of the bank. <PERSON> Spaggiari </PERSON> was arrested shortly after the break-in but escaped March 10, 1977. Two books, including <PERSON> Spaggiari </PERSON>'s own account, were written on the exploit and a film was made called `` The Sewers of Paradise.''
