<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, still smarting from his <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s stunning electoral defeat, received promises Saturday of economic assistance from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. He was greeted at the start of his two-day visit by pro-Solidarity demonsrators who demanded he resign. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, after a 3 -LCB- - hour meeting with <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, promised economic aid to encourage progress `` on the path of democracy and reform,'' according to a statement issued by Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s office It said the measures include a $ 7.75 million annual contribution to a managerial fund to train Poles in `` a more market-oriented economy.'' British sources said the promised help fell short of <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>'s hopes for new direct credit lines Supporters of Solidarity, the free union movement that won scores of victories in Sunday's election, demonstrated outside the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> and draped a statue with banners in Solidarity's red and white colors. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> commented on the election in an interview with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Channel 4 television network. `` We went into the election as a very fragmented front, in contrast to Solidarity,'' he said. `` Perhaps because we are burdened by a kind of complex of guilt for so far not having sufficiently applied all sorts of democratic procedures, we wanted to be super-democratic, super-pluralist,'' he added. <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, speaking Polish with his remarks translated into English, also said `` the reforms are irreversible and we're going to carry on with them.'' The statement from Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s office said she told <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> she welcomed the communist authorities' pro