<HEAD>Americans Returning From Beijing Bring Back Stories Of Turmoil</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA DE LA CRUZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dozens of Americans fleeing <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> arrived Saturday with vivid stories of Chinese students carrying corpses in the street, vehicles on fire and frenzied attempts by foreigners to escape the military crackdown. `` We felt like refugees,'' said <PERSON> Lorene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, who was on vacation with her mother, <PERSON> Sylvane </PERSON> <PERSON> Drake </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> graduate student feared arrested following the bloody crackdown in the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> capital arrived safely, his adviser said. `` Getting out of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was a fiasco,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> of the People to People Ambassador Program upon his arrival at <LOCATION> Seattle-Tacoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. `` At the airport, there was a lot of chaos, a tremendous amount of confusion,'' the <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> resident said. `` We were bumped off two flights.'' <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> flew three unscheduled charter flights from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Saturday, transferring passengers to regular flights out of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Many apparently still felt a sense of urgency even after reaching <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Passengers pushed through gates, said Capt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> of </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, who piloted <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> Flight 38 from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. Thirty-nine Americans who left <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> were listed on Flight 38, said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. Passenger <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Breitenbach </PERSON> was one of 40 <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, residents who traveled to <LOCATION> Baoding </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, their community's sister city. The group arrived last Sunday in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, and saw students carrying corpses on stretchers and countless military vehicles on fire, <PERSON> Breitenbach </PERSON> said. `` We saw people breaking wood to make clubs,'' <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> said. `` We were on the 15th floor of the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hotel </LOCATION>, and saw four buses on fire last Saturday and litters of people in the street.'' `` It was the saddest thing I've ever seen,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Durard </PERSON>, who is from <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and is with <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> to </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit group of health professionals who bring their medical expertise to other countries. `` We saw people with little babies in their arms, asking the soldiers to leave them alone,'' <PERSON> Durard </PERSON> said. `` Our guide was a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> doctor and he was crying and crying.'' <PERSON> Durard </PERSON> said some People to People participants wore black ribbons to show their support for the students. `` There is hatred of the Chinese government everywhere,'' she said. <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said that when the group was returning from a trip to the Great Wall, two lines of troops armed with rifles and bayonets surrounded their bus. The group `` hit the deck,'' he said. `` I did n't know what was going to happen.'' Group members made it back to the hotel safely, but were confined there. <PERSON> Breitenbach </PERSON> praised the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, which has been criticized by some returnees, for doing a `` fantastic'' job evacuating Americans. Some members of her group have already returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and others waited to come home. <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said he taped passengers' cheers as his flight left <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` When those wheels went up, it was great, but it was quite a tremendous emotional process,'' he said. `` We left behind some wonderful people. The government is just crushing them.'' Among the Chinese feared caught in the violence and the arrests that followed was Tong Boning, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> graduate student who took $ 8,000 in donations to pro-democracy protesters in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The 25-year-old man's last contact with friends in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was last Sunday, when he held his telephone to the window of his <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Hotel room to let a friend hear gunfire. <PERSON> Tong </PERSON> was last seen Monday trying to board a flight out of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. He did n't make it. On Saturday morning, he arrived in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, said adviser S.Y. <PERSON> Cheng </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> graduate mathematics department. `` He is very tired. In a couple of days, we will have a press conference and talk about it,'' <PERSON> Cheng </PERSON> said by telephone.
