<HEAD>Report: Six Foreign Hostages in Lebanon Moved to Iran To Ensure Safety</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Observer newspaper, quoting unidentified sources, reported Sunday that six Western hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> _ five Americans and one Briton _ have been moved to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to ensure their safety. The weekly identified none of the Americans but said the Briton was television journalist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>. Quoting unidentified sources in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>, it said <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> and two of the Americans were disguised as injured Lebanese, transferred to the <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> capital May 24 and flown to <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. The newspaper said three of the seven other Americans abducted by Iranian-backed Moslem extremists since 1985 were moved to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> on May 29. The Observer quoted the sources as saying <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s interior minister, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohtashami </PERSON>, decided to move the hostages after intensified fighting between Moslems and Christians since March that has left hundreds of people dead. The newspaper said <PERSON> Mohtashami </PERSON> `` has powerful leverage with Lebanese kidnap gangs.'' <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, 32, was snatched by gunmen as he headed to <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> after five weeks on a <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> assignment for London-based <ORGANIZATION> Worldwide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. The abduction took place two days after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bombing raid on <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. No group claimed responsibility. Altogether 15 Westerners, including nine Americans, are believed held by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem extremists in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The longest-held is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, kidnapped March 16, 1985.
