<HEAD>Bush Administration Has Doubts About Bhutto's Assurances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration believes <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is pressing ahead with a program to develop nuclear weapons despite its prime minister's assurances to the contrary, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Sunday editions. Unidentified administration officials quoted by the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> praised <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> for slowing some aspects of its atomic program that worry American analysts. However, they said there has been no slowdown in other areas, such as <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s longstanding worldwide efforts to buy parts and nuclear weapons technology. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> each year faces the cutoff of American military aid unless the president certifies that the country does not possess a nuclear device. Prime Minister <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> told President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this week that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> did not plan to make an atomic bomb. During her meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Webster </PERSON> took the unusual step of telling her in detail what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> knows about the <LOCATION> Pakistani </LOCATION> nuclear program. The officials said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had decided it was important to show Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> the extent of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' ability to monitor activities in her country, the Times said.
