<HEAD>Bentsen Wants To Up Limits On Earnings By Older Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said Saturday he plans to introduce legislation that would allow older Americans to earn more money while holding on to more of their Social Security earnings. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said his bill would increase both the amount of earnings a Social Security retiree can have with no reduction in benefits, as well as reducing the rate of reduction for those who earn over the limit. Under his proposal, a person who earned $ 15,000 in additional income over their Social Security benefit would be allowed to retain almost $ 800 more in Social Security benefits than under the present law, said the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat. Under the current Social Security earnings test, those 70 and older are eligible for full benefits without regard to earnings. But those under 70 are considered retired and eligible for full benefits only if their earnings are lower than a specified exemption level. In 1990, the maximum a retiree aged 65 to 69 could earn without suffering a reduction in Social Security benefits will be $ 9,360 under present law, said <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. He would boost that to $ 10,620. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said that under his plan a person age 65 to 69, earning $ 15,000 and receiving $ 8,000 in Social Security benefits, would lose $ 1,095 in benefits next year, compared with $ 1,880 under existing law. Retirees now typically lose all benefits when they have earnings in excess of $ 34,000. Under the <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> plan, a person with $ 8,000 in Social Security benefits would have to earn almost $ 36,000 before losing them all. Aides estimated that at least 600,000 Social Security beneficiaries would benefit from the changes proposed by <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>.
