<HEAD>Bush, in Switch, Focusing on Human Rights in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> four months ago, he declined to emphasize human rights issues. Now, faced with repression there on a grand scale, he is making it a focus of his <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> policy. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told an East Room news conference, `` We have to speak out in favor of human rights. We are n't going to remake the world, but we should stand for something.'' He also defended the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to harbor <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most famous dissident, astrophysicist <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON>, in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, saying `` It's awful hard when a man presents himself, a person who is a dissident, and says his life is threatened, to turn him back.'' `` That is n't one of the premises on which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was founded,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> added at the Thursday night news conference. <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> is now enjoying the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hospitality he was unable to claim last February when he was invited to be a guest of the president at dinner in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. On the final night of a three-day visit to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> hosted a Texas-style barbecue for Chinese leaders in a <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> hotel. But <PERSON> Fang </PERSON>, who has spoken out repeatedly against human-rights abuses in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, was barred from attending by Chinese police. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s protests did not come until the next day, amid some foot shuffling by the administration over who actually invited the dissident to the U.S.-hosted event _ the <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION> or the embassy staff. The president's slowness of response in the incident and his failure to stress the human rights issue _ either in public speeches or in private meetings with Chinese senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> _ drew criticism from some quarters. It also evoked comparisons with his predecessor, former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who often used public forums in communist countries to speak out forcefully on human rights. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in part, played down the issue during his visit so as not to offend top Chinese officials. He has a personal relationship with many of them. And he also has cited his familiarity with the Chinese sensitivity to criticism from outside on internal matters. However, any constraints <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> may previously have felt about denouncing human-rights abuses in clear terms were washed away with the bloodshed of the past week in <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. His spokesman said Friday, `` Keep in mind that the government has murdered many, many of its citizens. We have had an incredible upheaval in -LRB- that -RRB- country.'' Spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> added, `` Things are not going back to normal soon or in a quick fashion. ... A situation has been put in effect in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> that is going to have an influence on that country and on their relations with all countries of the world for a considerable period of time.'' As for the president, the personal relationships he established with senior Chinese leaders over the years since he served there as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoy in 1974-75 have been of little use to him in the current crisis. As he told his news conference, he put in a call to Chinese leaders but the line was busy. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> on Friday disclosed that the leader <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had been trying to reach was <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> himself. `` We were just informed the call would not go through,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` The call remains in place ... and of course, now it's public. I'm sure Chinese officials have read about it and so forth,'' the spokesman added.
