 to motivate you.'' The balance of $ 131,000 went to <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> at <PERSON> Watt </PERSON>'s request. <PERSON> Watt </PERSON> also testified he received $ 20,000 and $ 100,000 in consultant fees from similar arrangements with the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> group on projects in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Watt </PERSON> said he met on two occasions with <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> in early 1985 in connection with the projects and had several conversations with three other <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials _ <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, a special assistant to <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, <PERSON> Silvio </PERSON> <PERSON> DiBartolomeis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Barksdale </PERSON>, who both served as assistant secretary for housing during <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s tenure. <PERSON> Watt </PERSON> resigned as former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s interior secretary in October 1983. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> is the sole <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> secretary to remain with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> through both his terms as president. However, <PERSON> Watt </PERSON> said he was not aware when he met with <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> that <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> had set up a three-person panel in the department, including <PERSON> Dean </PERSON>, to select projects for mod rehab funding. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> and DeBartolomeis are scheduled to testified before <PERSON> Lantos </PERSON>' panel next week
