<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Americans appear to have fled <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> during the past week, spurred by the savage crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators and the advice of Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> that all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens should depart. According to figures released Friday by <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON>, slightly more than 1,500 Americans remained in the nation of 1 billion. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials had estimated that about 8,800 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens were in the country prior to last week's violence in which hundreds of demonstrators were killed by Chinese troops. Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> described <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> as `` still an armed camp.'' The White House on Friday denounced the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government's call for reprisals against the demonstrators and stressed that authorities there had `` murdered many, many of its citizens.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who placed a call to <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> earlier in the week but was unable to get through, had not heard back from <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> by Friday evening. `` The phone call remains placed and we'll see if he returns our call,'' presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. An administration source familiar with intelligence estimates said the number of Chinese troops in and around the capital city had grown to about 340,000 from 200,000 estimated earlier in the week. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> appeared in public Friday for the first time since May 16 to attend a ceremony at which he saluted military leaders for carrying out the crackdown on the `` counter-revolutionaries'' who had occupied <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Tiananmen Square until last weekend's military assault. Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s reappearance did not settle the question of who is in charge in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, nor does it clarify who bears responsibility for ordering the crackdown. `` We think that it's a very clouded situation, and we are n't in a situation to judge at this time to see who is in charge of what,'' she said. `` To be perfectly honest ... it seems to me that that would be something the Chinese should be telling us, versus us trying to sit back and guess.'' Said Fitzwater: `` You can watch television and see who the government is, but in terms of individual actions and motivations ... we do n't know.'' But he added that `` I do n't think anyone doubts'' that <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> are now in charge of the overall government in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> used some of the strongest language yet to express <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> condemnation of the military actions against unarmed civilians. `` Keep in mind that the government has murdered many, many of its citizens,'' said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. `` Things are not going back to normal soon or in a quick fashion.'' He noted calls for reprisals were being announced over the loudspeakers in the public squares in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. `` Reprisals are repugnant. We certainly watch this situation with grave concern,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> suspended military sales to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Monday but has refrained from economic sanctions, saying he does not want to cause hardship for the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people. Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said Friday there are approximately 500 Americans left in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, including 150 to 200 journalists and 116 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy