<HEAD>Israelis, Palestinians Face Divisions After 18 Months of Rebellion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Internal divisions among Palestinians and Israelis have been magnified by 18 months of bloodshed in the occupied lands and threaten to paralyze peace efforts. Leaders on both sides predict that, unless political progress is made soon, the violence will grow and destroy a historic opportunity for <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> negotiations. `` We are at a turning point, either to get a political solution or resort to more violence,'' said <PERSON> Said </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanaan </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> businessman who supports the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. `` We are waiting to see if we can reap all that we have planted in the past 18 months.'' At least 512 Palestinians have been killed and more than 8,000 wounded in the uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, which began its 19th month Friday. Twenty-two Israelis have been slain. Both societies have been polarized and advocates of violence are becoming more active. Palestinian militants insist only a violent struggle can lead to their own independent state. `` We are exposed to a lot of pressure to resort to violent means,'' <PERSON> Kanaan </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is growing mainly among the lower cadres of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and the population because the Israelis are pushing us so much against the wall.'' On the Israeli side, Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> speaks of harsher measures to crush the uprising and Jewish settlers are attacking Palestinian villages. A 13-year-old girl was killed in a recent raid. Leftists, by contrast, grow more vocal in demands for talks with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and formation of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state, both taboo in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> <PERSON> Oz </PERSON>, a prominent leftist writer, said extremism, including vigilante attacks by settlers, could destroy <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` We do n't want the nation to be ripped apart, but under no circumstances will we acquiesce in the transformation of our country into a monster,'' he told an audience of peace activists. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Alon </PERSON> <PERSON> Liel </PERSON> said in a telephone interview: `` If both sides lose control completely, the situation can deteriorate and we can have more violence.'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> faces increasing pressure in his conservative <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc to abandon plans for elections in the occupied lands that would choose <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> delegates to negotiate with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> has said he will resign if <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> rejects the plan at its convention next month. Mainstream <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> officials have conditionally accepted the elections as a first step toward negotiating a permanent settlement, but militants reject any compromise. `` I think only the continuation of the uprising will bring us liberation,'' said <PERSON> Sufian </PERSON> <PERSON> Khatib </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> physician whose views have been linked to those of the Popular Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, a radical pro-Syrian faction of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. `` The only obstacles are the compromises the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leadership is making,'' he said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> must focus its efforts only on the uprising and its continuation.'' Moderates say the uprising is a means of forcing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to negotiate. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has refused contact with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, which it defines as a terrorist organization. `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will find no alternative but to talk with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Faisal </PERSON> <PERSON> Husseini </PERSON>, a moderate from Arab east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will be forced to approach us as a people with a leadership and rights.'' <PERSON> Yossi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahimeir </PERSON>, a close aide to <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would not bow to violence and would crush the rebellion. `` The Arabs have two alternatives: to continue with the uprising or enter the circle of peace,'' he said. `` They will achieve nothing through the uprising.'' <PERSON> Liel </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said: `` If they reject elections, I do n't see in the future any plan that will pull us out of the circle of violence.''
